[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 3/8 answer="Let \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold and \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals sold.\n\nFrom the problem:\n1. Teresa sells small stuffed animals at $4 each, so the total revenue from small stuffed animals is \\( 4S \\).\n2. She sells large stuffed animals at one-third the price of small stuffed animals, so they cost \\( \\frac{4}{3} \\) dollars each.\n3. She sells twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones, so we have \\( S = 2L \\).\n\nTeresa's earnings can also be expressed as the sum of the revenue from both types of stuffed animals:\n\\[ 4S + \\left(\\frac{4}{3}\\right)L = 120 \\]\n\nSubstitute \\( S = 2L \\) into the equation:\n\\[ 4(2L) + \\left(\\frac{4}{3}\\right)L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 8L + \\frac{4}{3}L = 120 \\]\n\nTo eliminate the fraction, multiply through by 3:\n\\[ 3(8L) + 3\\left(\\frac{4}{3}\\right)L = 3(120) \\]\n\\[ 24L + 4L = 360 \\]\n\\[ 28L = 360 \\]\n\nNow solve for \\( L \\):\n\\[ L = \\frac{360}{28} \\]\n\\[ L = \\frac{90}{7} \\approx 12.857 \\]\n\nSince the number of stuffed animals must be an integer, let’s check our calculation again carefully:\n\n\\[ 8L + \\frac{4}{3}L = 120 \\]\nMultiply through by 3:\n\\[ 3(8"
