[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 2/3 answer='Let \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold, and let \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals sold.\n\nGiven:\n1. Small stuffed animal cost = \\$4\n2. Teresa earned \\$120 in total.\n3. Teresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones.\n4. Each small stuffed animal costs \\$4.\n\nFirst, calculate the revenue from selling all small stuffed animals:\n\\[ \\text{Revenue from small stuffed animals} = 2S \\times \\$4 \\]\n\nNext, express the revenue from large stuffed animals using the relationship between the prices given in the problem. Let the price of each large stuffed animal be \\( P \\). According to the problem, the price of a large stuffed animal is three times the price of a small one:\n\\[ P = 3 \\times \\$4 = \\$12 \\]\n\nTeresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones:\n\\[ S = 2L \\]\n\nCalculate the total amount of money Teresa earned from both types of stuffed animals:\n\\[ \\$120 = (2L \\times \\$4) + (L \\times \\$12) \\]\n\\[ \\$120 = 2L \\times \\$4 + L \\times \\$12 \\]\n\\[ \\$120 = \\$8L + \\$12L \\]\n\\[ \\$120 = \\$20L \\]\n\nSolve for \\( L \\):\n\\[ L = \\frac{\\$120}{\\$20} \\]\n\\[ L = 6 \\]\n\nNow, substitute \\( L = 6 \\) back into the equation \\( S = 2L \\) to find the number of small stuffed animals sold:\n\\[ S = 2 \\times 6 \\]\n\\[ S = 12 \\]\n\nThus, Teresa sold 12 small stuffed animals.\n\nThe answer'
